## The Exam

### Format (from mock)
- 60 minutes, 40 points, 3 parts, 10 questions
- All questions must be answered
- **Justification is mandatory** — a correct answer with no reasoning scores 0
- P ≠ NP may be assumed

### Three Parts
| Part | Focus | Points |
|---|---|---|
| Part 1: Knowledge | Conceptual recall, comparison, reasoning | 20 |
| Part 2: Application | Trace algorithms on given inputs | 10 |
| Part 3: Problem Solving | Coursework-style open problem (wildcard) | 10 |

### Critical Warning: Mock ≠ Real Exam
This professor is known for scaling the actual exam significantly beyond the mock — in a comparable module (LZSCC.111 Software Development), the mock had ~40pts/60min and the real exam had 100pts/120min with far more complex questions. The mock shows **which topics** matter, not **how hard** the questions will be.

**What this means in practice:**
- Expect algorithm traces to be on larger, more complex inputs
- Expect multi-variant questions: "here are 4 implementations — which are correct and why?"
- Expect justification to be load-bearing, not optional flavour
- Part 3 is likely a real meaty problem — code comprehension, algorithm design, or bug-fixing at coursework difficulty

